<p>International students or anyone with a personal connection to a non-listed climate impact may propose a non-listed challenge with Mr. Ignash's approval by Block 7.</p>

<h2>The 5-section Brief structure</h2>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Executive Summary</strong> (1 page or 60 sec) — Headlines only: what's the challenge, what does the science say, what's your top recommendation. Government officials may read only this part — make it count.</li>
  <li><strong>Background — the climate science</strong> (~1 page) — Briefly explain the underlying climate physics — greenhouse effect, projected warming, regional context — at a level appropriate for the GCC audience. Cite IPCC.</li>
  <li><strong>Evidence + Projected Impacts for Chennai</strong> (~1.5 pages) — What's happening now? What's projected over 20 years, 50 years? Where are the uncertainties? Use IPCC + local data + GCC Climate Action Plan.</li>
  <li><strong>Recommendations</strong> (~0.5 page) — 3-5 specific, evidence-anchored, actionable recommendations. Each one: what to do, why, rough cost or feasibility, equity implications. <em>Avoid</em> "raise awareness" — name specific actions the Corporation can take.</li>
  <li><strong>Sources</strong> — Cite everything. Consistent format. End of document.</li>
</ol>

<h2>Required components</h2>
<ul>
  <li>5 brief sections (above)</li>
  <li>OPVL on 3 sources — one IPCC or government source (IPCC AR6, GCC Climate Action Plan), one local/news or NGO source, and the AI source you used. Each with at least one <em>specific</em> Limitation, cited in the Brief. (Component 5, locks Block 11.)</li>
  <li>AI Documentation Template (required if AI was used at any stage; Component 6, locks Block 11)</li>
  <li>Policy Panel Q&amp;A defense in Block 12 (4 min pitch + 3 min Q&A)</li>
</ul>

<h2>What you'll be scored on</h2>
<p>The Chennai Climate Brief does triple duty: it assesses unit content (climate physics, IPCC science, regional projections, adaptation/mitigation distinction), it exercises <a href="/foundations/opvl-framework/">OPVL</a> on IPCC + government + AI sources, and it sharpens the policy-audience writing the year-arc has been building toward.</p>
<p><strong>Grade weighting</strong>: Brief 70% · Policy Panel 15% · Formative work (Blocks 1-9 activities, OPVL practice, peer feedback) 15%.</p>

<p><strong>Rolling-summative reminder.</strong> The K/U / T/T / C bands below describe the <em>overall</em> strand verdict. Under this unit's rolling-summative pattern, you get a band on each component as it locks (see the component due-date table above). The holistic strand mark at the end is the combination of those per-component bands — strong components lift the holistic verdict, weak components pull it down, and there's no end-of-unit re-mark of components that already locked. Mr. Ignash's running rubric in Google Classroom is where you see this strand-by-strand as the unit progresses.</p>

<div class="callout warn">
  <div class="callout-title">Three components to watch — band caps that carry into your strand mark</div>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>T/T — Recommendations (Component 2, locks Block 9).</strong> If your 3-5 recommendations are vague ("raise awareness," "more research," "protect the environment") or unsupported by your brief's own evidence, the locked T/T-recommendations band can't exceed 3-4 Developing — and that band is part of your overall T/T mark. Other strong T/T components (Evidence + Impacts, OPVL) can lift the holistic verdict, but they can't substitute for generic recommendations. Specific, actionable, evidence-anchored is the move.</li>
    <li><strong>K/U — AI Documentation log (Component 6, locks Block 11).</strong> Same as U0 / U1 / U2. If you used AI and the log is missing or trivial by Block 11, the K/U-AI-Doc band scores 1-2 Limited (the work isn't there to evaluate). Other K/U components (feedback diagram, Background) can lift the holistic K/U verdict, but the missing component still pulls it down. The documentation is the work, not an add-on.</li>
    <li><strong>C — Policy voice (Components 7–9, lock Block 12).</strong> Same trap as U2 — strong technical content delivered in academic-paper voice (not adapted to the GCC audience) caps the C components at 5-6. Same content, different presentation. Audience awareness is the C skill we're building.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<h2>Rubric — K/U / T/T / C across 4 bands</h2>

<h3>K/U — Knowledge &amp; Understanding</h3>
<p><em>The student recalls facts, terms and definitions while also explaining concepts, ideas, processes, themes. The student learns and performs skills related to their studies.</em></p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>7-8 (Exemplary):</strong> Exemplary knowledge of climate science. Energy balance, greenhouse effect, carbon cycle correctly applied. IPCC findings accurately characterized with correct interpretation of scenarios, confidence levels, uncertainty ranges. Discipline vocabulary used precisely. Chennai context accurately described.</li>
  <li><strong>5-6 (Proficient):</strong> Proficient knowledge. Most concepts correctly applied; minor errors. Chennai context mostly accurate.</li>
  <li><strong>3-4 (Developing):</strong> Some knowledge with gaps. Concepts applied but with errors. Vocabulary inconsistent. Chennai context superficial.</li>
  <li><strong>1-2 (Limited):</strong> Little knowledge. Concepts misapplied or absent. No Chennai-specific context.</li>
</ul>

<h3>T/T — Thinking &amp; Transfer</h3>
<p><em>The student plans for learning by formulating questions, generating ideas, researching. The student thinks critically. The student applies knowledge to unfamiliar contexts.</em></p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>7-8 (Exemplary):</strong> Highly effective translation of climate science into adaptation reasoning. Recommendations evidence-anchored, specific, actionable; address cost, feasibility, and equity. OPVL rigorously applied with specific Limitations identified. Cross-source synthesis sophisticated. Projected impacts reasoned, not just cited.</li>
  <li><strong>5-6 (Proficient):</strong> Proficient adaptation reasoning. Recommendations reasonable, most evidence-anchored. OPVL applied but Limitations may be general. Projected impacts present but may overstate certainty.</li>
  <li><strong>3-4 (Developing):</strong> Some translation but underdeveloped. Recommendations generic or unsupported. OPVL weak. Impacts listed rather than reasoned.</li>
  <li><strong>1-2 (Limited):</strong> Limited transfer. Recommendations missing or unrelated to evidence. No adaptation reasoning.</li>
</ul>

<h3>C — Communication</h3>
<p><em>The student expresses and organizes ideas in multiple forms. The student adapts communication to different audiences. The student uses conventions, terminology and vocabulary relevant to the discipline.</em></p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>7-8 (Exemplary):</strong> Genuine policy voice — concise, audience-appropriate, action-oriented. Executive Summary stands alone. Vocabulary precise but explained where needed. Citations clean. Policy Panel Q&amp;A confident, substantive, specific. AI Documentation clearly written.</li>
  <li><strong>5-6 (Proficient):</strong> Mainly clear with logical structure. Some sections slip into academic voice. Vocabulary mostly precise. Citations proficient. Panel responses clear but may miss depth.</li>
  <li><strong>3-4 (Developing):</strong> Somewhat clear; structure attempted but reads as student paper. Voice inconsistent. Vocabulary errors. Citation problems.</li>
  <li><strong>1-2 (Limited):</strong> Unclear. No policy voice. Beginner-level vocabulary. Citations missing.</li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Reporting format.</strong> Each strand is reported as its own band score (e.g., "K/U 7, T/T 6, C 7"). Not summed. The triplet IS the grade.</p>

